<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05156n"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05156n">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05156n"> 156(n)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> cavesson / finces</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Fanny Fitz and Mr. Alexander peered into the dark and vasty interior of the cow-house; from a remote corner they heard a heavy breath and the jingle of a training bit, but they saw nothing. &ldquo;I have the <mark>cavesson</mark> and all on her ready for ye, and I was thinking we&apos;d take her south into Mr. Gunning&apos;s land. His <mark>finces</mark> is very good,&rdquo; continued Johnny, going cautiously in; &ldquo;wait till I pull her out.&rdquo; <small> Somerville and Ross, <a name="ROSS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ROSS"><cite title="source">All on the Irish Shore</cite></a> (1903) [Fanny Fitz&apos;s Gamble] 45</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Cavesson: A kind of nose-band of iron, leather, or wood, &lsquo;fixed to the nostrils of a horse, to curb or render him manageable through the pain it occasions.&rsquo; (Stoqueler, <i>Mil. Encyc.</i>) (OED) </mm> </dd></dl>
